node.text: A true pioneer in both underwater filmmaking and shark research, Valerie Taylor is a living legend whose life’s work has become the basis for much of what we know about sharks today. Follow this daring ocean explorer’s trajectory from champion spearfisher to passionate shark protector in Playing With Sharks, now streaming on @disneyplus

node.text: Rio De Janeiro, Brazil: Witness the inspiring story of Tuany, a 23-year-old ballet dancer who started a dance company for young girls in the middle of one of Rio De Janeiro’s most dangerous favelas. She gives students hope for a better future and a safe space away from the violent world around them.

node.text: Grand Caillou/Dulac, Louisiana, U.S.A.: Meet Chief Shirell, the first female chief of her southern Louisiana tribe. Her ancestors have lived on the land for hundreds of years, and they are now expected to be among the United States’ first climate refugees. Chief Shirell can’t stop the storms, but she is impacting the legacy of her ancestors, the lives of her community today and the future of her people.

node.text: Memphis, Tennessee, U.S.A.: Meet Kayla, who has dedicated her life to helping homeless transgender women of color in Memphis, Tennessee. Having experienced homelessness and violence herself, Kayla has created a safe community for these notoriously discriminated-against people. She is building more than two dozen houses across Memphis for transgender women who need safety and a place to call home.

Photos by @lynseyaddario / These first two images are from the Dixie Fire, burning near the Butte Lake campground in the Northern California's Lassen National Forest, on August 26. The Dixie Fire, which has already burned over 820,000 acres (332,000 ha), is the second largest fire in California history. There are nearly 5,000 firefighters assigned to fight the fire, which is roughly 48% contained.

The last image is from the Caldor Fire, as it rips through the valley near the Sierra at Tahoe ski resort, south of Lake Tahoe, on  August 29. Dozens of houses burned along Highway 50, and the fire continues to travel in the area. The Caldor Fire has burned 200,000 acres (80,000 ha) and is 18% contained. node.text: Photo by @michaelchristopherbrown / Cubans watch the military convoy transporting Fidel Castro's ashes from Havana to Santiago, in December 2016. Along the thousand-kilometer (600 mi) route we saw very few stretches of road without people. They had traveled from north and south to watch the caravan pass—walking for miles or carried in by trucks, buses, or horse carriages to stand in remote areas, often dozens of miles from the nearest town. Fidel came to power in 1959 and died on November 25, 2016, at 90. His ashes were taken to the Santa Ifigenia Cemetery, where his brother Raúl placed the urn inside a giant boulder and behind a marble plaque inscribed simply with “Fidel,” next to the grave of Cuban independence hero José Martí. Follow @michaelchristopherbrown for more human stories from around the world.

node.text: Photo by @dzalcman / Members of a color guard of Native women service members pay their respects at the burial site of six Rosebud Sioux children who were laid to rest in their traditional territory last month. They were among the earliest wave of Native children sent to the Carlisle Indian Industrial School, in Pennsylvania, the first of hundreds of government boarding schools meant to forcibly assimilate Indigenous children into white, western culture. Conditions were bleak, and students were routinely exposed to physical, emotional, and psychological abuse. About 200 Native children died during the 39 years that Carlisle operated, and most were buried on the school grounds—now a U.S. Army barracks. After years of lobbying, a group of Lakota youth were able to push for the repatriation of their relatives after 140 years, and their remains made the journey home with them last month. For more, follow @dzalcman + @bmorinstories and check out the link to our recent story in the @natgeo bio.

node.text:
Photo by @thomaspeschak / I spend most of my time as a marine photographer, so what on Earth am I doing in South Africa’s Kalahari desert, 400 miles from the nearest ocean? Definitely no sharks or manta rays here, but lots of inquisitive meerkats. 

When the COVID-19 pandemic hit, I was set to work on National Geographic assignments in far-flung corners of the world. Instead it canceled my international travel plans, forcing me to look for stories to photograph closer to home—South Africa. I live in the mountains a few hours outside Cape Town, and “closer” ended up being a two-day drive north. 

During 2020 and 2021 I spent more than four months based at the Tswalu Kalahari Reserve, working with the @tswalufoundation to tell the story of the unique animals and plants that inhabit this extreme environment, and how climate change will dramatically impact this entire ecosystem. 

The story, "Edge of Survival," was published in the August issue of the magazine. Click the link in our bio to read more. Follow @thomaspeschak for more photographs from Africa’s wild places. #kalahari #meerkats #climatechange #wildlifephotography #wilderness #wild

node.text: Photos by Robin Hammond @hammond_robin / This is Zahra, an Afghan refugee living in Greece. She says: “Some Europeans think refugees don’t have hope, and they don’t have any strength, any skill. But no, it’s not true.” Zahra joined an initiative I created with @Witness_Change to support refugees in telling their own stories. With the support of @opensocietyfoundations we trained and mentored 40 refugee storytellers in Europe. They are producing a thousand portraits and interviews of other refugees on the continent. They're taking back their narrative. Zahra spoke to many Afghan refugees in Greece, including those in these portraits she made (photos 2 to 5). "After making interviews with them," she says, "the only thing [similar] between all of them is that they have hope.” See more of this work by following @zahragardi1 @1000Dreams.

node.text:
Photos by David Chancellor @chancellordavid / In Kenya's Reteti Elephant Sanctuary, a veterinarian team headed by the extraordinary Stephen Chege quietly and quickly assembled to assess the future of an orphaned elephant called Long’uro. In less than 24 hours, Mary, a caregiver, had established a powerful bond with the new arrival that now stood calmly in a makeshift operating room as anaesthesia slowly coursed through his broken body. Once he was asleep, the team could see in detail the damage caused to his trunk and face by  hyenas that attempted to drag him from a well he had fallen into. The surgeon carefully cleaned his wounds, removed 
loose and torn skin, and neatly closed the lesions on his trunk, which hopefully would allow it to heal quickly in the African sun and limit the possibility of infection. For the following days Mary would keep the wound clean, and the veterinarian would often check in on his progress. Mary waited for Long’uro to wake up, and then stayed with him as he recovered from the procedure. I visited often for the next weeks and months and continued to document his recovery. The final frame was taken in January 2021, about 9 months after the first image. I’ll continue to follow his journey through life. To see more follow me @chancellordavid.

node.text: Photo by Aaron Huey @argonautphoto / This is an image I took of members of the Taliban (identified by local police), who had come down from the mountains to harvest opium in the province of Oruzgan, Afghanistan, in 2007. I was on assignment, covering the drug war and the eradication of the opium poppies that grew in the tens of thousands of acres in the province. The men were offering themselves as day laborers in crowded circles on every corner of the main intersection in Tarinkot, the provincial capital. I walked into one of the crowds with my camera above my head, trigger pressed, slowly lowering as I approached the center to make the image. The smiling man on the right appeared to be hiring and negotiating rates. One of the men in the crowd likely was not a laborer but there to oversee the collection of taxes on the raw opium gathered, to pay for the Taliban to continue its fight against the Western forces. Now, as I watch helplessly from the sidelines thousands of miles away, I’m keenly aware that the Taliban will now decide the future of all Afghans. They will decide the fates of Afghan women and children, artists and poets, kite makers, intellectuals—everyone. The Taliban have already begun whipping people in the streets to enforce Sharia law, and my fear is that soon they will begin to cut off the hands of thieves, and organize public executions in stadiums, and stonings in the villages, like they did in their initial takeover of Afghanistan pre 9/11. I feel we have failed Afghanistan in too many ways to count and name here, but especially in this botched exit. We are leaving no one—and everyone. To see more images of the Taliban in Afghanistan follow @argonautphoto.

Photo by @paoloverzone / Scott Maloney, a photographer for the Cambridge University Library, prepares to photograph a 10th-century Masoretic Bible fragment. 

Maloney is part of a unit tasked with digitizing all content, including manuscripts, fragments, and documents ranging from a few millimeters to a few meters in length. The Cambridge Digital Library is a public database of 735,000 items, viewed from every country in the world. Maloney is one of five photographers whose processes include multispectral imaging, 3D imaging, traditional studio work, video,  and photogrammetry (3D modeling).

The process for photographing an artifact involves using a stand for a flat fragment, color calibration (comparing the image to a reference in order. to create a color profile, ensuring consistency and reliability for research). The unit abides by the highest standard of the heritage photography world—standards that are constantly evolving with the technology. Follow @paoloverzone for more photos and stories.

node.text: Photo by @dina_litovsky / In New York's Meatpacking District, slaughterhouses and gritty market stalls have given way to some of the flashiest nightclubs in the city. Each weekend, young women in heels carefully navigate the district's cobblestone streets, ready to unwind after the workweek. At the end of the night, shoes come off and hot dog stands welcome tired partygoers. This was photographed in 2015. For more images, follow me @dina_litovsky.

As one of only two on the planet, Najin is surrounded constantly by armed guards to protect her from poaching. Rangers like these men have become some of the northern white rhinos' greatest advocates. They know exactly how precious they are.
